# Git workflow

## Branches

- **`main`** — Production-ready; on shared repos, protect it and merge via PR when collaborating.
- **`develop`** — Integration branch for ongoing work (when the repository uses a two-branch flow).
- **Feature branches** — Create from `develop` (or `main` if your repo uses trunk-based flow). Use prefixes: `feature/`, `fix/`, `hotfix/` plus a short kebab-case description.

## Naming

- Branch names: `feature/add-inventory-export`, `fix/login-redirect`, `hotfix/payment-timeout`
- NetSuite scripts repo may use `{type}/{initials}/{short-description}` per project docs.

## Commits

- Use **Conventional Commits**: `feat(scope): summary`, `fix(scope): summary`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, etc.
- Keep commits focused; one logical change per commit when practical.

## Pull requests

- Open a PR for merges into `main` or `develop` when working with others or when your hosting requires it.
- Describe what changed and why; link issues or specs when applicable.
- Solo repos: direct pushes to `main` are fine if that is your workflow.

## Review

- Shared or production-sensitive repos: have at least one review before merging to `main` when practical.
- Address review feedback before merge.

## Releases

- Tag semantic versions (`v1.2.0`) when releasing; update `CHANGELOG.md` in the same change set as the release.
